	multiple channels process multiple streams of data that are assigned by a PBDMA(push buffer DMA))(ready channels are contained by a runlist (channels are stored in GPU managed instance memory)
	pushbuffer -> ring buffer allocated in memory or VRAM 
	putting everything together we have a small number of PBDMAs that serve the purpose of mappping a pushbuffer(maybe any in number as they basically are pointers to virtual addresses) to channel(1:1 to pb in terms of quantity not necessarily mapping) from the runlist
	All communication must take place thru GMMU -> maps virtual addresses to physical addresses on VRAM and DRAM
	within one channel  ->  strictly FIFO
	across channels     -> scheduled timeslicing via runlist

>LINKING WITH CUDA
	1)cudamalloc essentially allocates memory in VRAM , maps it in GMMU , stores it in the GMMU oage table
	2) kernel launch esssentially places the command on the ring buffer on the VRAM or DRAM which is then picked up a runlist channel assigned by the PBDMA

>To truly understand the necessity and the inner communication pipeline between the GPU ,CPU and memory we must understand addressing :
:1: Addressing can be thougth of as a method for a particular device to access the memory per se unique to the address space held by a device. Hence it is not essential that multiple addressing schemes necessarily be coherent.
:2: So what are the most obvious forms of addressing utilized by multiple components of the system :  Direct physical address spaces , CPU virtual address space , GPU virtual address space, IOMMU virtual address space (for a general PCIe device like a sATA or a NIC they would directly use IOMMU/direct physical(unsafe)addressing since they lack their own virtualizationlayer)
:3: while reasons for having GMMU and CPU MMU may be obvious - process isolation , security , illusion of virtually inifnite space the same cant be said for the IOMMU . the IOMMU is a hardware unit between mem controller and root complex across the PCIe interconnect to ensure kernel safety which resolves the physical address and sends it to the memory controller then the DRAM.
					
CPU ←→ memory controller ←→ RAM
              ↑
            IOMMU         
              ↑
         root complex
              ↑
           PCIe bus
              ↑
             GPU


>THE IDEAL FLOW : 

 Full memory access flow — after GMMU is initialized:
 GPU engine (PGRAPH/PFIFO) wants address X
    → X is a GPU virtual address
        → GMMU translates X → physical address P
            → is P in VRAM?
                YES → VRAM controller fetches it
                      stays inside GPU, fast
                NO  → P is in system RAM
                      crosses PCIe
                      IOMMU on CPU side translates P → actual system physical
                      system RAM fetched
                      returns over PCIe

>FOR now we will be limted to such a design due to lack of a GMMU:

 Full memory access flow — CPU doing DMA to GPU (before GMMU setup):
 CPU wants to send data to GPU
    → dma_alloc_coherent allocates physically contiguous system RAM
        → returns CPU virtual address (for CPU writes)
        → returns DMA address (physical, for GPU to use)
            → CPU writes commands into buffer using virtual address
                → MMU handles CPU side transparently
            → CPU tells PFIFO "pushbuffer is at DMA address P"
                → PFIFO puts P on PCIe bus
                    → IOMMU translates P → actual system physical
                        → system RAM fetched
                            → data arrives at GPU



